Q: List for me the newest trends in XAI
A: 1. Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) models for eXplainable AI (XAI): These models combine information retrieval with language generation capabilities to provide more accurate and contextually relevant explanations in XAI systems [2].

2. Similarity-Aware Training Cost-free Virtual User-Item Interactions for Multimodal Recommendation: This approach utilizes a similarity-aware training strategy for virtual user-item interactions, enhancing the explainability of recommender systems by considering multiple modalities [6].

3. Ontology-Based Knowledge Graph Framework for Industrial Standard Documents: By structuring industrial standard documents using hierarchical and propositional structures in a knowledge graph, understanding and interpreting these complex documents becomes more transparent and explainable [7].

4. Exploiting the Randomness of Large Language Models (LLM) in Text Classification Tasks: This method locates privileged documents in legal matters by analyzing the randomness of LLMs in text classification tasks, improving XAI performance in legal applications [10].

5. Detecting Privileged Documents by Ranking Connected Network Entities: In this approach, privileged documents are detected by ranking connected network entities, enhancing explainability in document review processes [11].

Confidence: 85%. To increase confidence, consider crawling more recent entries from the Information Retrieval section of arXiv (https://arxiv.org/list/cs.IR/new) and checking for updates on XAI-specific resources or publications.

A: 1. SIMA 2: An Agent that Plays, Reasons, and Learns With You in Virtual 3D Worlds, Google DeepMind [1]. This AI innovation from November 2025 allows agents to play, reason, and learn in virtual 3D worlds, enhancing the interaction between artificial intelligence and users.

2. Gemini Achieves Gold-Medal Level at the International Collegiate Programming Contest World Finals, Google DeepMind [1]. In September 2025, the AI system called Gemini reached a gold-medal level performance in the International Collegiate Programming Contest World Finals.

3. Aeneas Transforms How Historians Connect the Past, Google DeepMind [1]. Announced in July 2025, Aeneas is an AI system designed to help historians better interpret, attribute, and restore fragmentary texts by contextualizing ancient inscriptions.

4. Llama: Foundational Models from Meta AI [2]. Meta's Llama models are foundational models that aim to advance the state of AI research, but specific dates and details about their capabilities have not been provided in the linked resource.
